### Error Handler Responding Sets Transaction Name (Node.js)

Source: https://github.com/newrelic/node-newrelic/blob/main/documentation/transaction-naming-philosophy.md

This code showcases how an error handler middleware that sends a response will determine the transaction name, even if the initial route execution was different. In Express, this scenario is handled, but other frameworks might require more explicit instrumentation to correctly name transactions originating from error paths.

```javascript
const newrelic = require('newrelic');
const express = require('express');

const app = express();

app.get('/foo', function(req, res, next) {
  next(new Error('woops!'));
});

app.use('/:wat', function(err, req, res, next) {
  // Send the response from the error handler.
  res.send(500, 'Oh no!');
});

app.listen(8080);
```

